You need two pieces: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and a **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on EditProductPage

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// EditProductViewModel.cs
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard your changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard) return;
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 2. Guard the system back gesture / hardware back button

The `CancelCommand` above handles taps on your custom button, but the user can also swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page is EditProductPage
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        // Must get deferral BEFORE any await
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard your changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because the check is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- Call `GetDeferral()` **before** any `await`, then `deferral.Complete()` when done.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default back-arrow tap, so your `CancelCommand` handles that path. `OnNavigating` catches swipe-back and hardware back.
- To avoid a double-prompt (both paths firing), set a flag in `CancelCommand` before calling `GoToAsync("..")` and check it in `OnNavigating`, or skip the guard when navigation was programmatically initiated.
